According to an article by Trip Savvy, drivers in New York City should be tipped an average of 10 to 20 percent of the total cost of a ride. Most of the time, this amount is automatically calculated based on the cost of the fare. However, this value is not fixed and can change if the expectations of the passenger are not meet by the quality of the overall ride. To look deeper into what exactly influences the total tip for a New York City taxi ride, a dataset recording taxi rides and their characteristics was analyzed. The overall percentage of tip for taxi rides in New York City is above 20 percent. Furthermore, tip has a negative correlation with the total fare amount and varies by borough drop off location.

The data were analyzed in three distinct ways; in a macro level, by borough level, and by looking at rides from and to La Guardia Airport. First, at a macro level, the average percentage tip for taxi rides in the entire New York City area was off 24.50 percent of the total trip. There is an overall decreasing trend of the percentage tip as the total amount of fare increases. A possible explanation for this is customers paying with cash for rides under 20 dollars prefer to round up their tip. For lower total fare amount, rounding up to the nearest dollar has a more significant influence on the overall percentage tip than for more substantial fares. Finally, the number of passengers on a ride has a 0.045 percent significant positive influence on the percentage tip.

On the following graph, you can see that the when the total fare amount is under 20 dollars, the percentage tip is 20 to 25 percent displayed in yellow. Passed 40 dollars the mean percentage tip is less than 15 percent for all zones.

New York City is segmented into five boroughs; Bronx, Brooklyn, Manhattan, Queens, and Staten Island. Out of these, Manhattan overall tip in percentage is 0.86 percent less than the total percentage tip. On the other hand, Queens and Staten Island are both significantly higher percentage tips of 2.81 percent and 8.25 percent.

Furthermore, Manhattan was analyzed since it has a smaller percentage tip than the overall mean and has significantly more rides than the other zones. The following plot displays all taxi rides that were dropped off in the Manhattan area by zone. The mean percentage tip is 20 to 25 percent for rides that are on average lower than 17.5 dollars.

Finally, by looking only at rides leaving La Guardia Airport, the percentage tip could be compared to the overall rides. This limited the influence of other variables that could indirectly be influencing the percentage of tip. By segmenting the Manhattan area into five neighborhoods, we found that the Upper West Side has the highest percentage tip. However, it has a total median fare is $32.06 which is not the lowest in the area. The lowest mean fare is for Uptown Manhattan which has the lowest percentage tip from all the neighborhoods.
